  "prompt": "Why Modi government is not appointing Lokpal?",
  "response": "The issue of Lokpal appointment has been a complex and contentious matter in India. Here are some key points regarding the Modi government's stance on Lokpal:\n\n1. Delayed Appointment:\n- Despite the Lokpal and Lokayuktas Act being passed in 2013, the appointment process has been slow\n- The government has been criticized for not filling the Lokpal position in a timely manner\n\n2. Selection Process Challenges:\n- The selection requires consensus among high-profile members like the Prime Minister, Chief Justice of India, and Leaders of Opposition\n- Differences in opinion and selection criteria have led to delays\n\n3. Political Considerations:\n- Some critics argue that the government might be reluctant to establish a strong anti-corruption body that could potentially investigate high-ranking officials\n\n4. Legal Proceedings:\n- There have been legal challenges and debates about the selection procedure\n- The Supreme Court has also intervened in the matter at different points\n\n5. Current Status:\n- The Lokpal was finally appointed in March 2019, after significant political pressure and legal interventions\n- The first Lokpal chairperson, Justice Pinaki Chandra Ghose, was appointed\n\nWhile the government maintains that the appointment process followed legal procedures, critics continue to argue that the delays were deliberate and intended to avoid strict anti-corruption scrutiny.",
